		<article id=3D"post-5821" class=3D"post-5821 post type-post status-publis=
h format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-android tag-andorid ta=
g-ota">
	<div class=3D"entry-content">
	=09
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full"><img fetchpriority=3D"high" deco=
ding=3D"async" width=3D"747" height=3D"493" src=3D"https://web.archive.org/=
web/20250324153351im_/https://alaskalinuxuser3.ddns.net/wp-content/uploads/=
2023/11/wget.png" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-5822"></figure>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-9ba83=
971b4331a79d909749eefe68be4">One of the many tools in the toolbox of the An=
droid phone developer is that of downloading OTAs. An OTA is an Over The Ai=
r zip file that contains an update for your Android phone. This zip file wi=
ll have a lot of very useful information and files in it, which you can use=
 to develop custom roms for the phone. If you can get ahold of one, it can =
also serve as a great backup to your system, provided that you have the sto=
ck boot image/recovery image, so you can flash back to this OTA you downloa=
ded.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-8b061=
c7b57613b052b85c25fb938af8e">NOTE: Not all OTA=E2=80=99s are created equal.=
 Sometimes they are small and only include a few files, not the whole syste=
m, and don=E2=80=99t make a very useful download because you cannot use the=
m as a backup or pull enough information to create a custom rom. However, i=
f you plan to use it for that purpose, try to grab one that updates the And=
roid version of your phone.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-aab71=
63a5b65dacc8f863f8b66a43937">The downside to grabbing these OTA updates is =
that your phone may not have any, or after accepting one, it may be a long,=
 long time before another OTA update. Either way, here is how I grabbed one=
 for the CAT S42G.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-648a5=
6238ce3e9facfb711ff909fa301">It was brand new in the box, and I already kne=
w that it would come with Android 10 preinstalled. I also knew that there w=
ould be an OTA update waiting for it, which was a system update to Android =
12. I knew this because I owned one before opening this one. Another way yo=
u might know this is by looking up the phone online, such as GSM arena. If =
it says that it came with Android 10, but is upgrade-able to Android 12, yo=
u can be pretty sure that what you open in the box is the original software=
, and that it will <em>eventually</em> take an OTA to update to Android 12.=
 I say eventually because sometimes they take them in series, as incrementa=
l ones, and sometimes they just go to the latest one. It depends on the com=
pany and carrier mods, etc.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-d8aa0=
70e2bd47c570da7de7a8800c45d">Turning on the phone, go through the setup, wi=
thout a sim card, and don=E2=80=99t connect to the WiFi, so that the phone =
has no internet connection.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-1ad26=
9c03548ec4bd47fd14df4b76207">Then, go to settings, and enable developer mod=
e by clicking rapidly on the build number until it says you have enabled de=
veloper mode.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-569b6=
ad9ef5c152d3298f836fa93018f">Go to the developer mode, and turn on ADB (And=
roid debugging), and connect the phone to your computer.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-39a04=
5cd5f7234520009d3fbb3d093da">On the computer, open a terminal (I use Linux)=
, and start a logcat like so:</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-23e96=
9cc0d14c717f13d06285dfe51ab">$ adb logcat |tee ota.txt</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-668a6=
fa9c68aacda272d6171a7d494df">You may need to accept on the phone touch scre=
en, depending on your brand and settings. This starts pulling a log of ever=
ything the phone is doing and displaying it to you in the terminal, as well=
 as writing it down in a file called ota.txt.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-ee856=
ee73b27e6e1761ebf6be3965849">On the phone, enable the WiFi, connect to a ne=
twork, and go to the settings and check for an update. Since there was an u=
pdate in my case, it says the update information and started downloading it=
.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-7e594=
aa9e258b435afb9b81233ac0dd1">At this point, I turned off the WiFi to preven=
t the full download of the OTA update. On the computer terminal, I pressed =
control-c, to stop the logcat from logging.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-493f5=
27233b80ffb5bfa875d794130f1">Now I reviewed the large text file by grepping=
 the information I was looking for:</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-ae04a=
61c8edf31b19aa184d432a30af0">$ cat ota.txt |grep zip</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-5563d=
4a6644465f665e506e7dd744585">This showed me every line in the file with the=
 word zip in it. There were roughly 50 lines that met this criteria, some o=
f which were useless, like this one:</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-4845f=
5bfaccbe504904d6e69a573d672">11-14 12:20:42.538 10007 10037 I FirebaseCrash=
ApiImpl: FirebaseCrashApiImpl created by ClassLoader dalvik.system.Delegate=
LastClassLoader[DexPathList[[zip file =E2=80=9C/data/user_de/0/com.google.a=
ndroid.gms/app_chimera/m/00000004/DynamiteModulesC.apk=E2=80=9D],nativeLibr=
aryDirectories=3D[/data/user_de/0/com.google.android.gms/app_chimera/m/0000=
0004/DynamiteModulesC.apk!/lib/armeabi-v7a, /data/user_de/0/com.google.andr=
oid.gms/app_chimera/m/00000004/DynamiteModulesC.apk!/lib/armeabi, /system/l=
ib, /product/lib]]]</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-2f94f=
9ffde368d72bcb2ba6a003f5cee">But, as I scroll through there, I found this o=
ne:</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-b1bf8=
1c23d6d61b3ee45a5017d5c6296">11-14 12:20:40.767 2559 2961 I SystemUpdate: [=
Control,InstallationControl] Update URL changed from =E2=80=9C=E2=80=9D to =
=E2=80=9Chttps://ota.googlezip.net/packages/ota-api/package/cf1f7c3fa1596c8=
7f045cee1508823c98667fa06.zip=E2=80=9D.</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-3385a=
58912f79675cc01caa652e4a012">Sometimes, you can type your command like this=
:</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-3c236=
3aa21b75424205f9ff53a2bd259">$ cat ota.txt |grep zip |grep http</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-e186e=
37c73c2d6d2157988c745912bd0">To only get lines with both the word zip and h=
ttp in them, which makes an even shorter list, usually only 4 or 5, typical=
ly. Looking at the line with the OTA update in it, I could use the computer=
 to download just the OTA itself:</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-85e44=
5c3e5de97c876fddb5631d02e45">$ wget https://ota.googlezip.net/packages/ota-=
api/package/cf1f7c3fa1596c87f045cee1508823c98667fa06.zip<br>=E2=80=932023-1=
1-14 08:25:01=E2=80=93 https://ota.googlezip.net/packages/ota-api/package/c=
f1f7c3fa1596c87f045cee1508823c98667fa06.zip<br>Resolving ota.googlezip.net =
(ota.googlezip.net)=E2=80=A6 2001:4860:4802:32::70, 216.239.32.112<br>Conne=
cting to ota.googlezip.net (ota.googlezip.net)|2001:4860:4802:32::70|:443=
=E2=80=A6 connected.<br>HTTP request sent, awaiting response=E2=80=A6 302 F=
ound<br>Location: https://ota-cache1.googlezip.net/packages/data/ota-api/pa=
ckage/cf1f7c3fa1596c87f045cee1508823c98667fa06.zip?always_serve=3Dyes&amp;b=
aany=3Dall&amp;ipbypass=3Dyes&amp;mm=3D49&amp;ms=3Daya [following]<br>=E2=
=80=932023-11-14 08:25:02=E2=80=93 https://ota-cache1.googlezip.net/package=
s/data/ota-api/package/cf1f7c3fa1596c87f045cee1508823c98667fa06.zip?always_=
serve=3Dyes&amp;baany=3Dall&amp;ipbypass=3Dyes&amp;mm=3D49&amp;ms=3Daya<br>=
Resolving ota-cache1.googlezip.net (ota-cache1.googlezip.net)=E2=80=A6 2001=
:4860:3::4, 209.85.137.4<br>Connecting to ota-cache1.googlezip.net (ota-cac=
he1.googlezip.net)|2001:4860:3::4|:443=E2=80=A6 connected.<br>HTTP request =
sent, awaiting response=E2=80=A6 200 OK<br>Length: 1406052757 (1.3G) [appli=
cation/octet-stream]<br>Saving to: =E2=80=98cf1f7c3fa1596c87f045cee1508823c=
98667fa06.zip=E2=80=99</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-dddad=
ea4670fe4fce75d661c1c906069">cf1f7c3fa1596c87f04 100%[=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D&gt;] 1.31G 1.06MB/s in 12m 19s</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-200d6=
d4d5bd07dd3704f6cafa114f560">2023-11-14 08:37:22 (1.81 MB/s) =E2=80=93 =E2=
=80=98cf1f7c3fa1596c87f045cee1508823c98667fa06.zip=E2=80=99 saved [14060527=
57/1406052757]</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-e3402=
445cddb46c156cad4fc1d7725a7">alaskalinuxuser@alaskalinuxuser-CF-52NKE102M:~=
/Documents/phones/catS42g$</p>



<p class=3D"has-black-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-87dc8=
ef817d2d2bd5ea4f6afc5b3eaa4">Now you have an OTA zip file that you can work=
 with! You may wonder what to do with it, well, you could try using adb sid=
eload to fix another phone that you dorked up while messing around, or you =
can use tools like dumpyara. Other options are unzipping it and breaking do=
wn the payload.bin file to get what you need.</p>
